WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:04.680
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:23.660 --> 00:00:25.180
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Good evening,
ladies and gentlemen.

00:00:25.180 --> 00:00:28.170
Welcome. Thank you for
joining us this evening

00:00:28.170 --> 00:00:29.470
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:29.470 --> 00:00:30.770
My name is Nicholas Brown.

00:00:30.770 --> 00:00:32.070
I'm a music specialist
and one of the producers

00:00:32.070 --> 00:00:34.170
of the Library's Concert Series.

00:00:34.170 --> 00:00:37.120
We're very pleased to have with
us tonight the Tallis Scholars

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:38.420
who don't need much
of an introduction

00:00:38.420 --> 00:00:40.180
because I'm sure we
all know how important

00:00:40.180 --> 00:00:43.390
and significant their work has
been over the last several decades.

00:00:43.390 --> 00:00:46.730
And for you especially we have a
treat and that is their director

00:00:46.730 --> 00:00:48.360
and founder, Peter Phillips,

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:51.790
who will be spending a few moments
preconcert with us here to talk

00:00:51.790 --> 00:00:55.400
about the work of the Tallis
Scholars, and we'll hopefully get

00:00:55.400 --> 00:00:58.610
into some of their really
significant groundbreaking work

00:00:58.610 --> 00:01:03.420
in the realm of recordings and also
developing their own record label,

00:01:03.420 --> 00:01:08.100
which is of course was very
novel back then, and now it seems

00:01:08.100 --> 00:01:10.410
like everyone's copying you.

00:01:10.410 --> 00:01:13.850
So the basic format is we'll
spend some time chatting up here.

00:01:13.850 --> 00:01:16.930
I have some questions for
Peter and then we'll open it

00:01:16.930 --> 00:01:19.420
up to a Q and A towards the end.

00:01:19.420 --> 00:01:22.890
And without further ado,
we will just jump into it.

00:01:22.890 --> 00:01:26.100
Peter, tonight is your debut
at the Library of Congress.

00:01:26.100 --> 00:01:27.400
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: It is.

00:01:27.400 --> 00:01:28.700
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Which
is exciting for us

00:01:28.700 --> 00:01:30.000
and hopefully exciting for you too.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:31.300
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Yes.

00:01:31.300 --> 00:01:32.600
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: What has been
your experience of touring

00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:36.690
in the United States over the
many tours that you've had?

00:01:36.690 --> 00:01:42.300
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Yes,
well, this is our 68th tour

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:45.810
to North America but
basically to the US.

00:01:45.810 --> 00:01:50.440
This is our 32nd concert in DC,
even though it's our first here.

00:01:50.440 --> 00:01:54.250
A lot of those were in the Foger
Shakespeare Library, actually.

00:01:54.250 --> 00:01:58.750
Quite a long time ago now.

00:01:58.750 --> 00:02:00.580
So I feel I know DC well.

00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:02.830
But so the question
really, I suppose,

00:02:02.830 --> 00:02:04.400
is how have the audiences changed?

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:05.700
Is that --

00:02:05.700 --> 00:02:07.000
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Yes, sure.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:08.300
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Yes.

00:02:08.300 --> 00:02:09.600
I can't remember.

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:17.670
The first tour was in 1981 when
we were all very much younger.

00:02:18.800 --> 00:02:21.390
And I just don't remember
what the --

00:02:21.390 --> 00:02:25.090 position:56%
I mean, there always seemed to be a
really enthusiastic response anyway,

00:02:25.090 --> 00:02:29.720
that this music is much loved
here and treated with respect.

00:02:29.720 --> 00:02:32.110
And that's always been the case.

00:02:32.110 --> 00:02:35.060
And I've been -- what
I've liked very much is

00:02:35.060 --> 00:02:39.880
that I felt I had free range to
choose music that I wanted to do

00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:42.670
and that you would like to
come and hear it basically.

00:02:42.670 --> 00:02:46.160
So I've experimented with
a lot of repertoire here,

00:02:46.160 --> 00:02:50.410
whereas in other countries
I can't necessarily do that.

00:02:50.410 --> 00:02:52.690
So thank you very much
for that opportunity,

00:02:52.690 --> 00:02:55.710
because one of the
delights for me is

00:02:55.710 --> 00:02:58.970
that the Renaissance period is
actually a big period of music,

00:02:58.970 --> 00:03:01.940
which a lot of people
don't know very well.

00:03:01.940 --> 00:03:05.850
And I've just really enjoyed
roaming through it, you know,

00:03:05.850 --> 00:03:09.050
really without anyone
telling me not to or wish

00:03:09.050 --> 00:03:11.700
that I was just doing the
Allegri Miserere in every concert

00:03:11.700 --> 00:03:14.370
or I don't know whatever
-- you know.

00:03:14.370 --> 00:03:17.050
I mean, that does happen
in places but not here.

00:03:17.050 --> 00:03:18.760
So it's been great.

00:03:18.760 --> 00:03:20.060
It really has.

00:03:20.060 --> 00:03:23.050 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Have you seen the
demographics of the audiences change

00:03:23.050 --> 00:03:26.730
at all over the years,
maybe in specific cities?

00:03:26.730 --> 00:03:32.940
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: No, I
think when we -- I don't know.

00:03:32.940 --> 00:03:36.610
No, I think the average age
has remained very much the

00:03:36.610 --> 00:03:37.910
same actually.

00:03:37.910 --> 00:03:41.290
I mean, children tend
not to come to this,

00:03:41.290 --> 00:03:45.690
unless it's got a really
catchy Christmas title.

00:03:45.690 --> 00:03:47.430
And then they're always
disappointed,

00:03:47.430 --> 00:03:50.210
because we're not doing
what they expect.

00:03:50.210 --> 00:03:54.940 position:56%
So that's not really -- though I
have had children come up, you know,

00:03:54.940 --> 00:03:59.730
at the end, and they've sat there
silent for two hours, enthralled --

00:03:59.730 --> 00:04:05.900
genuinely, I think, rather
than being told not to move.

00:04:05.900 --> 00:04:11.860
Yes, I mean, but then I don't
know sort of up to sort of 30 --

00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:13.640
not so many people, I think.

00:04:13.640 --> 00:04:16.580
But after that, I think -- I'd
say it's grouped in the 30s or 40,

00:04:16.580 --> 00:04:20.230
50 range probably and
has remained like that.

00:04:20.230 --> 00:04:22.630
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: In your current
and most recent tours of the US,

00:04:22.630 --> 00:04:25.140
have you ended up in cities
that you had not performed

00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:26.440
in before, or is it --

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:27.740
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: All the time.

00:04:27.740 --> 00:04:29.040
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Oh, really?

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:30.340
How about on this tour?

00:04:30.340 --> 00:04:31.640
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Well,

00:04:31.640 --> 00:04:32.940
on this tour I've never
been to Harrisonburg.

00:04:32.940 --> 00:04:34.240
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Where is that?

00:04:34.240 --> 00:04:35.600
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: No idea.

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:37.650
[ Laughter ]

00:04:37.650 --> 00:04:40.200
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Sorry
for anyone from there.

00:04:40.200 --> 00:04:43.500
I'm from up north so --

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:45.750
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Every
tour there's somewhere.

00:04:45.750 --> 00:04:48.170
Laramie, Wyoming --
that's quite good.

00:04:48.170 --> 00:04:50.810
Yes. Makes you think.

00:04:50.810 --> 00:04:53.070
Well, actually the problem with
Laramie, Wyoming is that it's

00:04:53.070 --> 00:04:58.210 position:56%
so high up that we find it hard to
breathe properly when we're singing.

00:04:58.210 --> 00:05:02.360
Let alone conducting, certainly,
but [inaudible], anyway, I mean,

00:05:02.360 --> 00:05:05.790
there are all -- lots of
different experiences, yeah.

00:05:05.790 --> 00:05:07.580
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Just
out of curiosity,

00:05:07.580 --> 00:05:11.850 position:56%
and this is going a bit far afield,
the different venues you perform in,

00:05:11.850 --> 00:05:14.150
in the UK and maybe
London specifically,

00:05:14.150 --> 00:05:18.020
what kinds of things do you
do differently to prepare

00:05:18.020 --> 00:05:19.750
for performances in
the different venues?

00:05:19.750 --> 00:05:24.670
For example, Wigmore Hall versus
Cadogan Hall versus Albert Hall,

00:05:24.670 --> 00:05:25.970
if you've had anything
there recently.

00:05:25.970 --> 00:05:27.270
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: We have, yeah.

00:05:27.270 --> 00:05:30.660
Well, I mean, these are
vastly different venues.

00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:35.100
And we really have to adapt
to a lot of different spaces.

00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:38.110
And certainly the difference
between Cadogan Hall

00:05:38.110 --> 00:05:41.170
and the Royal Albert Hall
-- I mean, you could --

00:05:41.170 --> 00:05:44.740
don't know how many Cadogan Halls
you can fit into the Albert Hall,

00:05:44.740 --> 00:05:46.990
but it must be sort of like 50.

00:05:46.990 --> 00:05:50.520
It's a sort of -- if you stand
on the stage there and you look

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:52.890
at the audience, they're
about half a mile away.

00:05:52.890 --> 00:05:54.570
I mean, it's just incredible.

00:05:54.570 --> 00:05:56.130
And there's nothing
you can do about it.

00:05:56.130 --> 00:05:58.680
I mean, you have to -- you can't --

00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:01.770
if you over-sing, it's
not a good idea obviously.

00:06:01.770 --> 00:06:06.020
If you panic, it's not a good idea.

00:06:06.020 --> 00:06:10.040
But I think just -- you
just do what you do.

00:06:10.040 --> 00:06:11.610
There's nothing you can
do with the Albert Hall.

00:06:11.610 --> 00:06:15.200 position:56%
The audience have to get used to how
far away they are from the stage,

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:16.990
that's basically what it is.

00:06:16.990 --> 00:06:20.700
Whereas in Cadogan Hall, the
danger is that it's going

00:06:20.700 --> 00:06:24.360
to be too loud for everybody.

00:06:24.360 --> 00:06:27.090
So we have to sort
of tailor down a bit.

00:06:27.090 --> 00:06:29.430
But then there are those -- I
mean, there's also the difference

00:06:29.430 --> 00:06:31.220
in acoustical properties.

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:34.540
I mean, there are buildings like
cathedral buildings which tend

00:06:34.540 --> 00:06:38.730 position:56%
to have quite a lot of reverberation
but it's sort of not localized.

00:06:38.730 --> 00:06:40.030
It's sort of all round.

00:06:40.030 --> 00:06:43.890
So in those buildings,
we can relax in the sense

00:06:43.890 --> 00:06:46.920 position:56%
that that the building will probably
take the sound and round it.

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:49.940
So it makes our lives
a little bit easier.

00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:51.830
But they also make our
lives more difficult

00:06:51.830 --> 00:06:54.640
in that we can't hear
each other so well.

00:06:54.640 --> 00:06:58.190
So the ensemble gets a bit
more difficult to control,

00:06:58.190 --> 00:07:01.560
and I have to be very, very
precise with where the beat is,

00:07:01.560 --> 00:07:04.720
because that's when
people get lost, basically.

00:07:04.720 --> 00:07:06.060
And then there are those buildings

00:07:06.060 --> 00:07:08.140
that are huge buildings
but totally dry.

00:07:08.140 --> 00:07:11.330
I mean, bone dry, you
know, there's nothing.

00:07:11.330 --> 00:07:13.860
The sound stops in your throat.

00:07:13.860 --> 00:07:15.370
Those are awful places.

00:07:15.370 --> 00:07:19.320
But I mean, they can
be secular or sacred.

00:07:19.320 --> 00:07:22.190
In our experience, there's
not much difference.

00:07:22.190 --> 00:07:24.950
And people who say to us, "You
should always do this music

00:07:24.950 --> 00:07:28.570
in a sacred space," I don't
agree with them, necessarily.

00:07:28.570 --> 00:07:31.060
I mean, there are fantastic
symphony halls built

00:07:31.060 --> 00:07:34.850
to very modern specifications
of acoustical clarity --

00:07:34.850 --> 00:07:36.290
like the Birmingham Symphony Hall,

00:07:36.290 --> 00:07:37.800
where we're singing
this time next week --

00:07:37.800 --> 00:07:40.940 position:56%
which are just fantastic to sing in.

00:07:40.940 --> 00:07:44.010
They're so encouraging
and beautifully laid

00:07:44.010 --> 00:07:47.510
out to the audience, so that
audience are comfortable too --

00:07:47.510 --> 00:07:50.890
not always the case in cathedrals.

00:07:50.890 --> 00:07:52.190
I don't know.

00:07:52.190 --> 00:07:53.490 position:56%
Everyone has their own take on that.

00:07:53.490 --> 00:07:54.790
Yeah.

00:07:54.790 --> 00:07:56.610
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Could you tell us
a bit about the founding of Gimell

00:07:56.610 --> 00:07:59.760
and also maybe what
some of your goals were

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:01.060
and if those goals
have been achieved

00:08:01.060 --> 00:08:03.370
over the course of its longevity?

00:08:03.370 --> 00:08:05.450
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Yes, certainly
the goals have been achieved

00:08:05.450 --> 00:08:10.190
in that we've been able to just
record what we wanted to record

00:08:10.190 --> 00:08:15.380
and to experiment with repertoire
in a way that a big record label

00:08:15.380 --> 00:08:18.090
in the old days would never
have allowed us to do.

00:08:18.090 --> 00:08:22.470
They would -- there wasn't
enough famous stuff basically.

00:08:22.470 --> 00:08:27.820
So we -- I mean, the first
record we ever made was for EMI,

00:08:27.820 --> 00:08:29.120
and that had the Allegri on it.

00:08:29.120 --> 00:08:32.260
Well, you can't record the Allegri
over and over and over again,

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:35.060
obviously, because it's
diminishing returns.

00:08:35.060 --> 00:08:37.560
But with Gimell we were able to --

00:08:37.560 --> 00:08:44.140
we sold enough copies right from
the start to finance, experiment;

00:08:44.140 --> 00:08:48.480
we could experiment, take
risks, explore new music.

00:08:48.480 --> 00:08:49.890
And so, yes.

00:08:49.890 --> 00:08:54.230
And it started in 1980,
because nobody else wanted it.

00:08:54.230 --> 00:08:58.070
So I mean, actually we
did that EMI record,

00:08:58.070 --> 00:08:59.690 position:56%
and it was a great success actually.

00:08:59.690 --> 00:09:02.350
But that was it.

00:09:02.350 --> 00:09:05.540
And we came up with another
idea and, no, it was no good.

00:09:05.540 --> 00:09:09.980
They had to sell thousands and
thousands of copies every day.

00:09:09.980 --> 00:09:13.830 position:56%
And of course, what we've done is
sell thousands -- tens of thousands,

00:09:13.830 --> 00:09:16.330
hundreds of thousands copies
of some of those discs

00:09:16.330 --> 00:09:18.220
over a period of 30 years.

00:09:18.220 --> 00:09:21.230
But the record -- the big record
companies never had the tolerance

00:09:21.230 --> 00:09:23.210
for that.

00:09:23.210 --> 00:09:25.230
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: What kind
of medium were you using?

00:09:25.230 --> 00:09:28.590
Were you originally with CDs
or had you started with vinyl?

00:09:28.590 --> 00:09:29.890
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: No,
we started with vinyl.

00:09:29.890 --> 00:09:32.320
And it was very difficult.

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:37.840
This was in 1980 to
about 1984 when vinyl --

00:09:37.840 --> 00:09:40.730
everyone had got enough
vinyls in their lives

00:09:40.730 --> 00:09:43.570
and in their houses actually,
because they're very heavy.

00:09:43.570 --> 00:09:46.930
And those shelves of vinyls.

00:09:46.930 --> 00:09:50.860 position:56%
I heard of people's floors
collapsing under the weight of them.

00:09:50.860 --> 00:09:54.890
Anyway by about 1982,
everyone had had enough of it.

00:09:54.890 --> 00:09:59.230
And then we made our first digital
recording which wasn't for CD,

00:09:59.230 --> 00:10:03.460
but the digits were
available in '83.

00:10:03.460 --> 00:10:06.070
And then the first CDs became --

00:10:06.070 --> 00:10:09.500
were invented in '84,
I think it was.

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:14.460
And we were very quick onto them,
because we saw the potential.

00:10:14.460 --> 00:10:16.720
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: And now in this
climate of digital streaming

00:10:16.720 --> 00:10:21.920
and download and that kind of
business, how are you handling

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:23.230
that from a business perspective?

00:10:23.230 --> 00:10:24.530
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: It's disastrous.

00:10:24.530 --> 00:10:28.330
I mean, people are not
buying CDs anymore.

00:10:28.330 --> 00:10:33.790
And there's nothing to
replace the income from CDs.

00:10:33.790 --> 00:10:38.410
Downloading is okay,
but it's not nearly

00:10:38.410 --> 00:10:43.060
as good; and also it's dying off.

00:10:43.060 --> 00:10:48.130 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: I saw today the UK
numbers for November had vinyl sales

00:10:48.130 --> 00:10:51.610
above digital downloads for
the first time, which is wild.

00:10:51.610 --> 00:10:52.910
Yeah.

00:10:52.910 --> 00:10:54.210
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: That is wild.

00:10:54.210 --> 00:10:56.580
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: And it was like a
four-fold increase in vinyl sales

00:10:56.580 --> 00:11:00.060
from one year ago, on a monthly
basis, which is pretty interesting.

00:11:00.060 --> 00:11:01.710
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: There are a lot
of people out there who would love

00:11:01.710 --> 00:11:04.360
to think that vinyl is coming back.

00:11:04.360 --> 00:11:05.910
Maybe you're one of those.

00:11:05.910 --> 00:11:07.210
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: No, no, no, no, no.

00:11:07.210 --> 00:11:08.950
I have enough already.

00:11:08.950 --> 00:11:12.240
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: But, well,
the immediate problem is

00:11:12.240 --> 00:11:13.540
that CDs are not selling.

00:11:13.540 --> 00:11:18.180
And the substitute that's
killed the CD market off used

00:11:18.180 --> 00:11:21.170
to be okay and is now also falling.

00:11:21.170 --> 00:11:23.350
But streaming is the thing.

00:11:23.350 --> 00:11:26.290
So -- and we get almost
no revenue from it.

00:11:26.290 --> 00:11:28.400
It's really serious.

00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:31.250
But we simply have to change
the business model, I suppose.

00:11:31.250 --> 00:11:33.770
I mean, we can't pay
the fees to the singers

00:11:33.770 --> 00:11:36.480
or go to the interesting places
we used to go to, to record in,

00:11:36.480 --> 00:11:37.780
because we haven't got the money.

00:11:37.780 --> 00:11:41.010
So we've got to find the
money from some other way.

00:11:41.010 --> 00:11:44.460
And the symphony orchestras
are doing it by financing

00:11:44.460 --> 00:11:49.600 position:56%
from concert revenue, so the whole
thing is wrapped into one promotion.

00:11:49.600 --> 00:11:52.090
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Do you handle
distribution internally

00:11:52.090 --> 00:11:54.210
within Gimell, or do you
work with partners for that?

00:11:54.210 --> 00:11:58.220
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: No, we work
entirely with Hyperion actually.

00:11:58.220 --> 00:12:00.000 position:56%
And in this country, Harmonia Mundi.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:02.880
But they also have
gone -- basically gone.

00:12:02.880 --> 00:12:06.150
You know, those record
shops have gone,

00:12:06.150 --> 00:12:08.770
the distributors are cracking up.

00:12:08.770 --> 00:12:10.690
It's a terrible scene out there.

00:12:10.690 --> 00:12:11.990
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: It is.

00:12:11.990 --> 00:12:13.290
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: It's not
the end of the world, though,

00:12:13.290 --> 00:12:16.200
because I notice every
group is making records.

00:12:16.200 --> 00:12:18.510
I mean, there are more
records than ever.

00:12:18.510 --> 00:12:24.910 position:56%
No one's buying them, but groups
are making lots and lots of records.

00:12:24.910 --> 00:12:28.380
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: We have a nuclear
bunker filled with them, so,

00:12:28.380 --> 00:12:34.180
out in Virginia, at our National
Audio/Visual Conservation Center,

00:12:34.180 --> 00:12:35.560
which is pretty interesting.

00:12:35.560 --> 00:12:40.930 position:56%
And another thing that you've been
focusing on lately is the Foundation

00:12:40.930 --> 00:12:42.540
at Merton College, Oxford.

00:12:42.540 --> 00:12:43.840
Could you tell us a bit about that?

00:12:43.840 --> 00:12:45.140
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Yes.

00:12:45.140 --> 00:12:47.110
This is a wonderful idea.

00:12:47.110 --> 00:12:50.780
Merton College, Oxford is
the oldest college in Oxford

00:12:50.780 --> 00:12:52.360
or Cambridge in its foundation.

00:12:52.360 --> 00:12:54.510
It was founded in 1264.

00:12:54.510 --> 00:12:59.390
And before that, it was clearly
a group of students there --

00:12:59.390 --> 00:13:00.930
scholars, whatever you
want to call them --

00:13:00.930 --> 00:13:02.370
living in this sort of community.

00:13:02.370 --> 00:13:05.540
But that happened in
Oxford and Cambridge.

00:13:05.540 --> 00:13:08.890
But mostly earliest in Oxford.

00:13:08.890 --> 00:13:12.800
And the buildings that are there
for Merton are the early sort

00:13:12.800 --> 00:13:15.130
of -- what do you call it?

00:13:15.130 --> 00:13:17.700
Communal buildings for a
properly founded college.

00:13:17.700 --> 00:13:20.290
The chapel was started in 1264.

00:13:20.290 --> 00:13:22.340
And it was just a fantastic chapel.

00:13:22.340 --> 00:13:24.580
I mean, it's the size
of a small cathedral.

00:13:24.580 --> 00:13:27.250
It's architecturally
completely unspoiled,

00:13:27.250 --> 00:13:30.180
and there was no choral foundation.

00:13:30.180 --> 00:13:33.330
The choral foundations in
Oxford and Cambridge came later.

00:13:33.330 --> 00:13:36.780
They all came in the
14th and 15th centuries.

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:39.580
And we're talking about
the 13th here.

00:13:39.580 --> 00:13:41.660
So anyway, I said --
and wonderful sound.

00:13:41.660 --> 00:13:44.010
We'd been recording in
there for many years.

00:13:44.010 --> 00:13:47.850
I said to the warden, "Why is
there no choral foundation here?

00:13:47.850 --> 00:13:49.470
It's just elementary."

00:13:49.470 --> 00:13:54.650 position:56%
And the warden said, "I don't know."

00:13:54.650 --> 00:13:55.950
So we worked on it.

00:13:55.950 --> 00:13:58.620
And we got the money together.

00:13:58.620 --> 00:14:01.090
One of your countrymen
helped us quite a bit.

00:14:01.090 --> 00:14:02.390
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Oh.

00:14:02.390 --> 00:14:03.700
Great. Wonderful.

00:14:03.700 --> 00:14:05.110
Had you been Director of Music

00:14:05.110 --> 00:14:07.390
for a period already before
the establishment of the --

00:14:07.390 --> 00:14:09.620
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: No, I just
made records there for years.

00:14:09.620 --> 00:14:13.050
I mean, the history of that is that
we made records in Merton in the --

00:14:13.050 --> 00:14:15.860
when we started in the
'70s and early '80s.

00:14:15.860 --> 00:14:17.830
We then got noisy or
-- I can't remember.

00:14:17.830 --> 00:14:20.110
We went to the countryside
when we could afford to.

00:14:20.110 --> 00:14:21.990
We went to a lovely church
in the middle of nowhere

00:14:21.990 --> 00:14:24.190
