00:17:33.080 --> 00:17:36.430
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Are there any
specific interpretational issues

00:17:36.430 --> 00:17:41.700
that you are focusing on as
you go through this cycle?

00:17:41.700 --> 00:17:43.810
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Well, Josquin
is a very subtle composer,

00:17:43.810 --> 00:17:48.890
and he's not someone whose style
you can suddenly say that's

00:17:48.890 --> 00:17:50.770
definitely him.

00:17:50.770 --> 00:17:52.640
He's quite experimental.

00:17:52.640 --> 00:17:57.230
And that means it's difficult just
to say he should be done like this.

00:17:57.230 --> 00:18:02.460 position:56%
And I think that's underplaying him
anyway, to turn him into Palestrina,

00:18:02.460 --> 00:18:06.230
for example, who does have the same
style, more or less consistently,

00:18:06.230 --> 00:18:07.920
and there are merits in that.

00:18:07.920 --> 00:18:09.700
I love Palestrina's music.

00:18:09.700 --> 00:18:13.790
But Josquin is much more difficult
to -- just to say, "Okay, yep."

00:18:13.790 --> 00:18:17.160
So, and one -- and he poses
real technical problems.

00:18:17.160 --> 00:18:20.980
This is one of his things --
he writes ranges of voice --

00:18:20.980 --> 00:18:23.780
voice ranges that go two octaves,

00:18:23.780 --> 00:18:28.690
and modern singers are not
trained to singing like that.

00:18:28.690 --> 00:18:35.620
A tenor, so called, has a specific
range when you're learning tenor.

00:18:35.620 --> 00:18:40.310
And these parts just
wander all over the place.

00:18:40.310 --> 00:18:44.080
And we rather like a balanced,

00:18:44.080 --> 00:18:46.790
blended sound, from
top to bottom, up.

00:18:46.790 --> 00:18:49.280
It's quite possible that
Josquin didn't expect anything

00:18:49.280 --> 00:18:51.990
of the kind that we like.

00:18:51.990 --> 00:18:54.460
But I want to do it my way.

00:18:54.460 --> 00:18:57.470
And I'm not trying to impose -- I'm
not trying to take anything away

00:18:57.470 --> 00:18:59.940
from the music, but I'm
trying to impose a sound --

00:18:59.940 --> 00:19:02.780
trying to produce a sound
through it, if you like,

00:19:02.780 --> 00:19:07.310
that we will collectively find
attractive and enable us to listen

00:19:07.310 --> 00:19:09.800
to the music with pleasure.

00:19:09.800 --> 00:19:13.890
What he heard in his
time, we will never know.

00:19:16.200 --> 00:19:17.780
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: For the
program this evening,

00:19:17.780 --> 00:19:23.170 position:56%
is there a specific thematic thread
