00:19:23.170 --> 00:19:25.500 position:56%
that went into selecting the program

00:19:25.500 --> 00:19:28.380
and also the sequence
of the repertoire?

00:19:28.380 --> 00:19:29.700
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Well,
this is a Christmas program.

00:19:29.700 --> 00:19:32.090
I'm always being asked to put
-- at this time of the year.

00:19:32.090 --> 00:19:33.610 position:56%
It's a bit of a challenge, actually.

00:19:33.610 --> 00:19:37.590
Because there isn't that much.

00:19:37.590 --> 00:19:41.680
The Christmas music is much
more sort of popular music.

00:19:41.680 --> 00:19:47.090
Polyphony of the complicated
variety tended not

00:19:47.090 --> 00:19:48.510
to be written for cathedrals.

00:19:48.510 --> 00:19:52.090
It tended to be written
for courtly chapels,

00:19:52.090 --> 00:19:54.980
much smaller buildings
than a huge cathedral.

00:19:54.980 --> 00:19:58.170
And so it gets rather
specialized and I --

00:19:58.170 --> 00:20:04.050
so what I do, I've resorted to
doing is finding appropriate texts

00:20:04.050 --> 00:20:06.680 position:56%
normally to do with the Virgin Mary.

00:20:06.680 --> 00:20:11.490
So there's the Salve, the
Ave Maria, the Magnificat,

00:20:11.490 --> 00:20:14.480
which is actually an Advent
text, but we're in Advent,

00:20:14.480 --> 00:20:17.750
because we always tour
in Advent, actually.

00:20:17.750 --> 00:20:21.750
This Christmas thing
starts quite early.

00:20:21.750 --> 00:20:23.140
You may have noticed.

00:20:23.140 --> 00:20:28.860 position:56%
But Advent's rather a difficult --
I find Advent quite difficult to pin

00:20:28.860 --> 00:20:32.950
down conceptually, so -- but anyway
there are texts which go very well

00:20:32.950 --> 00:20:35.150
