So I would -- we hope we can, and
it would be great to have some

00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:03.900
of that stuff out of there.

00:25:03.900 --> 00:25:05.200
But it would cost.

00:25:05.200 --> 00:25:06.500
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Yeah.

00:25:06.500 --> 00:25:07.800
Do you have an American's
Friends group?

00:25:07.800 --> 00:25:09.100
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: No.

00:25:09.100 --> 00:25:10.400
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: You
might have members.

00:25:10.400 --> 00:25:15.020
Great. So I think we'll open it
up to questions, if that's okay.

00:25:15.020 --> 00:25:16.930
And if you have a question, just
stick your hand up in the air

00:25:16.930 --> 00:25:20.080
and my colleague Jay will bring
a microphone to you as we do want

00:25:20.080 --> 00:25:24.280
to record you for the
permanent archives.

00:25:25.890 --> 00:25:28.190
Select your wording accordingly.

00:25:29.990 --> 00:25:31.290
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:25:31.290 --> 00:25:35.170
I'm personally partial
to Josquin's motets.

00:25:35.170 --> 00:25:42.090
Do you have any plans to, in a
more minor way, explore the motets

00:25:42.090 --> 00:25:47.380 position:56%
at the same time you're
celebrating the masses in 2020, '21?

00:25:47.380 --> 00:25:52.630 position:56%
I understand you don't have a
project to record all of the motets,

00:25:52.630 --> 00:25:54.440
but are you going to
be fitting in --

00:25:54.440 --> 00:25:59.150
helping people understand
his non-misa repertoire?

00:25:59.150 --> 00:26:00.890
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Well,
yes, I hope so, very much.

00:26:00.890 --> 00:26:04.260
I mean, the thing about the
motets is they tend to be scored

00:26:04.260 --> 00:26:05.970
for more voices than the masses.

00:26:05.970 --> 00:26:07.660
One of the interesting
thing about the masses is

00:26:07.660 --> 00:26:10.830
that they're all scored
for four voices only.

00:26:10.830 --> 00:26:12.800
Whereas the bigger motets,
like the one you're going

00:26:12.800 --> 00:26:16.080
to hear this evening which is
in many ways the best of them.

00:26:16.080 --> 00:26:19.520 position:56%
This praeter rerum was -- this motet
that starts the concert tonight --

00:26:19.520 --> 00:26:23.080
was incredibly influential
at the time.

00:26:23.080 --> 00:26:25.930
I'm sure you know it, if you're
a follower of the motets.

00:26:25.930 --> 00:26:30.750
But it's got a sort of sonority
to it that's quite unique.

00:26:30.750 --> 00:26:32.050
And a lot of the composers

00:26:32.050 --> 00:26:35.760
that follow Josquin
took it up as a model.

00:26:35.760 --> 00:26:37.390
Anyway, that doesn't
answer your question.

00:26:37.390 --> 00:26:41.060
I mean, we do this motet a lot,
and there are plenty of others,

00:26:41.060 --> 00:26:42.820
I've just put down
the Pater Noster --

00:26:42.820 --> 00:26:45.880
you know, the Lord's Prayer
-- for a concert next year.

00:26:45.880 --> 00:26:47.720
But there are many of them.

00:26:47.720 --> 00:26:50.840
Well, I just decided -- in fact,
the motets are more famous.

00:26:50.840 --> 00:26:56.250
What I've done all my career is try
to put forward really good pieces

00:26:56.250 --> 00:27:00.020
that nobody knew at the
time that we recorded them.

00:27:00.020 --> 00:27:04.530
And that's helped quite a number of
composers become fairly mainstream.

00:27:04.530 --> 00:27:11.170
I could instance them,
but I -- anyway, yeah.

00:27:11.170 --> 00:27:17.750
So, but the motets are already
fairly well-established, so --

00:27:17.750 --> 00:27:22.140
while not all of them, I agree,
and there are a lot of them,

00:27:22.140 --> 00:27:24.540 position:56%
I just had -- I can't do everything.

00:27:24.540 --> 00:27:28.770
So we decided we'd do
the masses, and oh,

00:27:28.770 --> 00:27:30.590
I'd love to do some
motets with them.

00:27:30.590 --> 00:27:35.460 position:56%
Josquin tended -- well, didn't base
his masses on any of his own motets.

00:27:35.460 --> 00:27:38.090
So we're not going to get
that little neat sandwich

00:27:38.090 --> 00:27:42.020
that you can get with some of
these composers, like Palestrina.

00:27:43.590 --> 00:27:47.940
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Next
question, in the back?

00:27:47.940 --> 00:27:50.550
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I know y'all
did the premier

00:27:50.550 --> 00:27:53.300
of Tavener's last piece,
the Requiem Fragments.

00:27:53.300 --> 00:27:54.600
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Oh, yes.

00:27:54.600 --> 00:27:55.900
&gt;&gt; Wonderful piece.

