00:28:06.010 --> 00:28:08.360
"Well, my God, these guys --
people aren't really performing,

00:28:08.360 --> 00:28:11.490
and they really should
be performing"?

00:28:11.490 --> 00:28:12.790
Yeah, that sort of thing.

00:28:12.790 --> 00:28:14.200 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Yeah, Nico Muhly.

00:28:14.200 --> 00:28:15.590
I don't know if you've
come across him.

00:28:15.590 --> 00:28:16.890
He's American.

00:28:16.890 --> 00:28:18.190
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Oh, yeah.

00:28:18.190 --> 00:28:19.490
We've commissioned him.

00:28:19.490 --> 00:28:20.790
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Yeah.

00:28:20.790 --> 00:28:22.090
Hmm? Did you like the piece?

00:28:22.090 --> 00:28:23.390
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Yes.

00:28:23.390 --> 00:28:24.690
It was called Compare Notes,
and it was for Daniel Hope

00:28:24.690 --> 00:28:25.990
and Jeffrey Kahane, a violin piece.

00:28:25.990 --> 00:28:28.600
And then we got the
choir from Temple Church

00:28:28.600 --> 00:28:30.970
in London do his Magna Carta piece,

00:28:30.970 --> 00:28:34.540
when the Lincoln Cathedral
copy came here, two years ago.

00:28:34.540 --> 00:28:35.840
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Terrific.

00:28:35.840 --> 00:28:37.480
Well, there you go.

00:28:37.480 --> 00:28:41.570
So the Lincoln Center commissioned
Nico Muhly to write us a set

00:28:41.570 --> 00:28:45.980
of lamentations, which he did.

00:28:45.980 --> 00:28:48.750
And I think it's absolutely
fantastic.

00:28:48.750 --> 00:28:51.640
We've just been on
a tour of Australia,

00:28:51.640 --> 00:28:53.750
and we sang it every night.

00:28:53.750 --> 00:28:57.680
So we really know these
lamentations by Nico really well.

00:28:57.680 --> 00:29:00.950
And it goes -- it fits
very well with, you know,

00:29:00.950 --> 00:29:06.620 position:56%
the Renaissance settings; the Tallis
in particular we did alongside it.

00:29:06.620 --> 00:29:11.880
And it makes such as exciting -- if
the modern composers got it right,

00:29:11.880 --> 00:29:16.420
as Avo Part does, the
music matches up so --

00:29:16.420 --> 00:29:19.570
if it could be made to match up,
in the way that Part does it,

00:29:19.570 --> 00:29:23.250
with Renaissance style, then we
have a fantastic half of a concert,

00:29:23.250 --> 00:29:25.460
where we can just make
these comparisons

00:29:25.460 --> 00:29:26.760
and I find them thrilling.

00:29:26.760 --> 00:29:29.170
And I think they've
gone down very well.

00:29:29.170 --> 00:29:33.030
So I'm hoping Nico -- I think the
Lincoln Center are going to ask him

00:29:33.030 --> 00:29:36.390
to write a follow-up, so
I look forward to that.

00:29:36.390 --> 00:29:39.830
I mean, so the answer is
Arvo Part we sing a lot.

00:29:39.830 --> 00:29:41.650
But he's now, won't write anymore.

00:29:41.650 --> 00:29:44.930
He's 81. So I'm afraid that's that.

00:29:44.930 --> 00:29:47.760
And Tavener's dead,
and there's Nico.

00:29:47.760 --> 00:29:49.590
There's Eric Whitacre.

00:29:49.590 --> 00:29:50.890
He wrote us a piece.

00:29:50.890 --> 00:29:53.200
He was very, very good about that.

00:29:53.200 --> 00:29:54.650
I like that piece.

00:29:54.650 --> 00:29:58.530
He's very careful in the way he
wrote it, specifically for us.

00:29:58.530 --> 00:30:00.890
There's Gabriel Jackson
we've commissioned.

00:30:00.890 --> 00:30:04.900
Quite a few.

00:30:04.900 --> 00:30:06.200
&gt;&gt; Nick Brown: Great.

00:30:06.200 --> 00:30:07.890
Next question?

00:30:07.890 --> 00:30:10.690
&gt;&gt; This is really a
question out of ignorance.

00:30:10.690 --> 00:30:15.980
But I wonder if over time --
say, the last 30 or 40 years --

00:30:15.980 --> 00:30:20.220
research has revealed anything
that might have changed things

00:30:20.220 --> 00:30:22.950
in your performance practices?

00:30:22.950 --> 00:30:26.280
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips:
Well, that's -- yeah.

00:30:29.870 --> 00:30:36.240
If the scholars had been able to
find good evidence of how they sang

00:30:36.240 --> 00:30:41.490
in those days, that would
be very interesting.

00:30:41.490 --> 00:30:45.470
Because then we would know
whether we were on the --

00:30:45.470 --> 00:30:50.250
the early instrument thing was,
the whole thing was that they --

00:30:50.250 --> 00:30:53.570
the instruments they found were
what the composer was writing for.

00:30:53.570 --> 00:30:55.740
So you're then able
to produce the sound

00:30:55.740 --> 00:30:59.450
that the composer actually wrote
for, in those early orchestras

00:30:59.450 --> 00:31:01.700
or whatever those instruments
were playing.

00:31:01.700 --> 00:31:03.000
So the instruments are there.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:05.820 position:56%
You can play them and get the sound.

00:31:05.820 --> 00:31:08.440
We can't do that with our thing.

00:31:08.440 --> 00:31:12.050
So I'm left, I mean, in a rather
fortunate but ambiguous position

00:31:12.050 --> 00:31:18.370
of guessing and trying to make the
music come alive for today, for us.

00:31:18.370 --> 00:31:21.850
And the scholars can't
tell me that I'm wrong,

00:31:21.850 --> 00:31:24.560
but they certainly can't
tell me I'm right either.

00:31:24.560 --> 00:31:27.270
And then there's the question of --

00:31:27.270 --> 00:31:30.180
I mean, the scholarly arguments

00:31:30.180 --> 00:31:33.630
about speeds, pitch,
fixta [phonetic].

00:31:33.630 --> 00:31:35.940
I don't know if this means anything
to you, but I mean, there --

00:31:35.940 --> 00:31:37.410
but these arguments never change.

00:31:37.410 --> 00:31:39.300
I mean, in the 40 years
I've been going,

00:31:39.300 --> 00:31:41.820
I haven't heard -- I
mean, they had fads.

00:31:41.820 --> 00:31:43.760
You know, there were
fads of pronunciation.

00:31:43.760 --> 00:31:46.140
Latin was always --
suddenly about 30 years ago,

00:31:46.140 --> 00:31:48.030
Latin had to be pronounced
in the tradition

00:31:48.030 --> 00:31:49.670
that the composer came from.

00:31:49.670 --> 00:31:52.750
So we suddenly had German
Latin, French Latin.

00:31:52.750 --> 00:31:56.720
That lasted about -- really
inconveniently for about six years.

00:31:56.720 --> 00:31:58.020
Then it went away again.

00:31:58.020 --> 00:32:00.730
We could go back to our
very happily Italian Latin,

00:32:00.730 --> 00:32:03.890
which comes so much more
naturally and stop --

00:32:03.890 --> 00:32:06.350
so I mean, there are
fads, and there are fads

00:32:06.350 --> 00:32:07.650
of fickter [phonetic] as well.

00:32:07.650 --> 00:32:10.500
You can make it sound -- sort
of pre-Raphaelite, if you like,

00:32:10.500 --> 00:32:14.550
by not pushing any of
the cadence fickters.

00:32:14.550 --> 00:32:18.010
The pitch sing has come and gone
a bit, as you probably know.

00:32:18.010 --> 00:32:20.850
The English tend to transpose up.

00:32:20.850 --> 00:32:23.600
But that's sort of gone
again now, so it's settling

00:32:23.600 --> 00:32:26.230
down back towards written
pitch again.

00:32:26.230 --> 00:32:32.370
They don't know, and they argue
with each other all the time.

00:32:32.370 --> 00:32:34.950
So that -- what I have
to do in a rehearsal --

00:32:34.950 --> 00:32:37.080
you know, I've got an hour
to sort this thing out

00:32:37.080 --> 00:32:40.550
and get a performance
going for a big public --

00:32:40.550 --> 00:32:42.530
I'm just not going to
have academics arguing

00:32:42.530 --> 00:32:44.860
about it, just there and then.

00:32:44.860 --> 00:32:46.160
I mean, you have to
make a decision --

00:32:46.160 --> 00:32:47.680
this is how it's going
to be tonight.

00:32:47.680 --> 00:32:51.160 position:56%
Maybe not for the next, but
tonight, it's going to be like this.

00:32:51.160 --> 00:32:53.040
And it's usually --
someone always disagrees.

00:32:53.040 --> 00:32:57.970
And the last thing we want is
critics writing in big newspapers

00:32:57.970 --> 00:33:00.130
who are academics, because
they always have something

00:33:00.130 --> 00:33:02.420
to disagree with.

00:33:02.420 --> 00:33:04.720
&gt;&gt; Thanks.

00:33:16.430 --> 00:33:20.530
&gt;&gt; I don't think I can paraphrase
your first question to Peter,

00:33:20.530 --> 00:33:23.770
but I'm wondering if, Peter, you
could elaborate a little bit more

00:33:23.770 --> 00:33:29.840
on audiences around the world
and where you can do sort

00:33:29.840 --> 00:33:34.990
of maybe less experimental
things and why that is --

00:33:34.990 --> 00:33:37.460
whether it's a tradition,
cultural --

00:33:37.460 --> 00:33:38.760
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Yeah.

00:33:38.760 --> 00:33:40.060
&gt;&gt; Why?

00:33:40.060 --> 00:33:41.360
&gt;&gt; Peter Phillips: Well,

00:33:41.360 --> 00:33:44.920
in the Western Christian
world, it's one thing.

00:33:44.920 --> 00:33:47.950
At least the Latin is
something that they know --

00:33:47.950 --> 00:33:50.880
you know, the audience knows
existed, and they have a sort

00:33:50.880 --> 00:33:54.160
of sense of where the
music has come from,

00:33:54.160 --> 00:33:57.870
what the Ave Maria text might mean
to people, that kind of thing.

00:33:57.870 --> 00:34:02.260
But we've recently sung
a lot in China and Japan.

00:34:02.260 --> 00:34:04.620
And then you're dealing
with a very different setup.

00:34:04.620 --> 00:34:07.710
And very different between
those two countries, in fact.

00:34:07.710 --> 00:34:10.630
The Japanese are extremely
knowledgeable about this music

00:34:10.630 --> 00:34:13.330
and sing it themselves quite a lot.

00:34:13.330 --> 00:34:15.560
But they're not very adventurous.

00:34:15.560 --> 00:34:17.980
So when we go to Japan, we tend

00:34:17.980 --> 00:34:20.680
to sing the same pieces
over and over again.

00:34:20.680 --> 00:34:22.630
I can't experiment very much there.

00:34:22.630 --> 00:34:25.860
I can slip in the odd --

00:34:25.860 --> 00:34:29.920
sort of oddball piece
that gets by the censor

00:34:29.920 --> 00:34:32.700
but it's really -- I'll tell you.

00:34:32.700 --> 00:34:38.030
It's the Victoria Requiem,
Palestrina's Missa Papae Marcelli,

00:34:38.030 --> 00:34:42.390
Josquin's Missa Pange
Lingua, Tallis's Lamentations,

00:34:42.390 --> 00:34:45.330
the Allegri Miserere
in every concert.

00:34:45.330 --> 00:34:50.180
I'm not exaggerating too much.

00:34:50.180 --> 00:34:54.680
Now, in China, they have no
knowledge at all, and they put us

00:34:54.680 --> 00:34:58.350
on in these symphony halls, which
it's important to them to fill.

00:34:58.350 --> 00:35:02.690
So it really is extraordinary
business.

00:35:02.690 --> 00:35:05.810
I mean, they don't
know what to ask for,

00:35:05.810 --> 00:35:09.010
so I try to put together a program
which will -- and then they say,

00:35:09.010 --> 00:35:11.090
"Well, could we have Greensleeves?"

00:35:11.090 --> 00:35:14.360
So I say, "Yep.

00:35:14.360 --> 00:35:17.260
Yes. You can have Greensleeves.

00:35:17.260 --> 00:35:21.220
The rest of the concert will be
more like what we normally do.

00:35:21.220 --> 00:35:24.520
But I'm sure -- " and
then they can come up --

00:35:24.520 --> 00:35:28.790
the Koreans are very good at
coming up with local folk songs

00:35:28.790 --> 00:35:31.820
that have been arranged
for SATB a cappella.

00:35:31.820 --> 00:35:34.980
And we sing those as encores.

00:35:34.980 --> 00:35:37.510
And that's the way the
concerts are sold, really,

00:35:37.510 --> 00:35:41.940
that we'll do our own thing and
that's potentially interesting,

00:35:41.940 --> 00:35:45.670
but at the end, they'll get
something they really know.

00:35:45.670 --> 00:35:49.460
And one occasion -- it wasn't
Greensleeves -- what's that?

00:35:49.460 --> 00:35:50.760
Amazing Grace.

00:35:50.760 --> 00:35:53.410
Yes. The audience sang it with us.

00:35:53.410 --> 00:35:56.130
I had to conduct the audience.

00:35:56.130 --> 00:36:00.670
You know, having previously
just sung Tallis's Lamentations

00:36:00.670 --> 00:36:03.450
or something, we then --
the thing turned into much

00:36:03.450 --> 00:36:05.430
like a communal activity.

00:36:05.430 --> 00:36:09.510
And they loved it, and so,
yeah, we've been invited back.

00:36:09.510 --> 00:36:12.240
[ Laughter ]

00:36:12.240 --> 00:36:13.930
It's extraordinary.

00:36:13.930 --> 00:36:18.840
That doesn't wholly answer
the question but I think, yes,

00:36:18.840 --> 00:36:24.570
in the Western world -- in Italy,
they like Palestrina very much and,

00:36:24.570 --> 00:36:25.870
I mean, that's fine by me.

00:36:25.870 --> 00:36:27.170
There's so much to do.

00:36:27.170 --> 00:36:29.730
I can do anything within
some sort of guidelines.

00:36:29.730 --> 00:36:33.190
And very often we're asked to sing
in festivals which have a theme.

00:36:33.190 --> 00:36:37.810
The theme might be a city,
like Venice or Vienna.

00:36:37.810 --> 00:36:40.910
And then I love planning
those programs.

00:36:40.910 --> 00:36:42.880
And then I can get
away with experiments,

00:36:42.880 --> 00:36:45.180
because it fits the theme.

